r />Of _course_ "irq0" is a valid irq. On PC's, it's usually the timer <br />interrupt.<br /><br />It's the "dev-&gt;irq" _cookie_ zero that means it is does not have an irq.<br /><br />If you have a physical "irq 0" that is bound to a device, it needs a <br />cookie, and that cookie can't be 0, because that means the device has no <br />interrupt.<br /><br />How hard is that to understand? Why do people mix these up?<br /><br />		Linus</pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
